{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516202"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:39:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:39:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12571"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12571"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.12,0.76,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5070"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53493"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5070"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38964"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"},{"type":"tags","id":"1862"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15892"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53493"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of intermittent right heel pain. The pain is localised to the heel and sole of her right foot and is worse first thing in the morning and at the end of the day. It is non-radiating. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes managed with metformin. Her mother has osteoarthritis. She works as a house cleaner, has a body mass index of 30 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, is a non-smoker and drinks one standard drink of alcohol nightly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no masses, swelling or redness around the foot and ankle region. There is no tingling or loss of sensation in the foot. There are no abnormal bony prominences. Active and passive movements of the ankle are normal except for pain elicited on dorsiflexion and a positive windlass test. On palpation of the sole of her foot, there is some tenderness over the calcaneum; however, heel squeeze test is negative. There is also no Tinel sign elicited.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcaneal stress fracture","Achilles tendinopathy","Plantar fasciitis","Tarsal tunnel syndrome","Gout"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eplantar fasciitis\u003C/strong\u003E. Plantar fasciitis typically presents with heel pain that is worse with the first few steps in the morning or after periods of rest, and improves with activity. The pain is usually localised to the medial plantar aspect of the heel and may extend along the plantar fascia. Risk factors include obesity, prolonged standing or walking (as in this patient\u0027s occupation as a house cleaner), and sudden increases in activity level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcaneal stress fracture\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with more diffuse heel pain that worsens with activity. The heel squeeze test would likely be positive, and there might be localised swelling or bruising. This patient\u0027s negative heel squeeze test and lack of inflammatory signs make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchilles tendinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes pain in the posterior aspect of the heel or ankle, about 2-6 cm above the insertion of the Achilles tendon. The pain would be exacerbated by activities that load the Achilles tendon, such as running or jumping. The location of this patient\u0027s pain and the positive windlass test are more consistent with plantar fasciitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETarsal tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a compression neuropathy of the tibial nerve or its branches as they pass through the tarsal tunnel. It typically presents with burning pain, numbness, or tingling in the sole of the foot and toes. The absence of these sensory symptoms and a negative Tinel\u0027s sign make this diagnosis unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset of severe pain, often in the first metatarsophalangeal joint, accompanied by warmth, redness, and swelling. The gradual onset of symptoms, lack of inflammatory signs, and location of pain make gout an unlikely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe positive windlass test (pain with passive dorsiflexion of the toes) is particularly suggestive of plantar fasciitis. This test stretches the plantar fascia, reproducing the patient\u0027s pain. The tenderness over the calcaneum, particularly at the medial calcaneal tubercle where the plantar fascia inserts, is also characteristic of plantar fasciitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Plantar fasciitis is one of the most common causes of foot pain in adults aged 40-60 years.","First-line treatment for plantar fasciitis is conservative, including stretching exercises and appropriate footwear.","Plantar fasciitis typically presents with heel pain that is worse in the morning and after periods of rest."],"references":["Buchbinder R. Plantar fasciitis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2022 [ Cited 2023 Mar 3]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/plantar-fasciitis","Trojan T, Tucker AK. Plantar fasciitis. Am Fam Physician. 2019;99(12):744-750. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2019/0615/p744.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38964"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12571"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38964"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-22T09:28:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-22T09:29:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5070"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53493"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":nu